-- English                                                                               
Software requirements are generically defined as:
a) The set of conditions/needs that the software must satisfy in order to achieve a specific objective;
b) The constraints on its design and operation.
The topics in this KA detail the systematic way in which Software Engineering should deal with Requirements. All the concepts that this area encompasses are used in the Software Life Cycle Process called "Software Requirements Analysis" which, although often associated with the early period of software development, is an activity that extends throughout the life cycle of a software product.');

As part of the software life cycle, it is a process in which requirements are analyzed to produce a description of the internal structure of the software that will serve as the basis for its construction. The result of this process describes the Software Architecture, i.e., how the software is decomposed and organized into components and the interfaces between those components.
During the Design process, engineers produce various models that form a kind of blueprint (or diagram) of the solution to be implemented. These models can be evaluated to verify that they effectively meet the product requirements.
Despite the similarity of the term, Software Design does not refer only to the construction of the graphical components of the software, this activity being only a small subpart of the much more comprehensive KA Software Design.');

Software Construction is strongly linked to Software Design and Software Testing, since the construction, as a process, uses the artifacts resulting from the Design process and feeds the Testing process.');

As an activity, Testing consists of the dynamic verification that a program provides the expected behaviors for a finite set of test cases appropriately chosen from the domain of typically infinite executions.');

Maintenance has become increasingly important now that companies are trying to get the most out of their software investment by extending the life of their software products.');

With the use of tools such as version control and baselines (fixed set of configurations at a certain point in time), it is thus possible, on the one hand, in case of problems, to determine what was changed and by whom and finally to correct, and on the other hand, in case of software stability, to replicate its configuration in a controlled manner.');

Software project management encompasses a set of skills with a decisive impact on its systematic implementation.
Among the different aspects that an engineer has to manage in a software project are the application of specific standards of the organization to which he belongs, human resources management (whether at the level of hiring, training, career progression), communication management with a team and cost management.');

Examples of these activities are requirements, design, construction, testing, and configuration management, among others.
Software processes are specified with various objectives such as: facilitating human understanding, communication, and coordination; assisting in the management of software projects; measuring and improving software quality in an efficient manner; supporting process improvement and providing a basis for automatic support of process execution.');


In short, Software Quality is the reflection of how well a software product meets the requirements of the same product.');

Due to the increasingly widespread impact that software has on people''s lives, engineers must possess a set of professional and personal characteristics that allow them to carry out their activity in a consistently conscientious manner, resulting in the creation of software with known and reliable characteristics.
Professional practice thus means a way of conducting a service with the aim of achieving a certain standard or criterion, not only in the process of carrying out the service but also in the final product of that same service.');

Economics is the study of value, costs, resources and the relationship between them under a given context. In the discipline of Software Engineering as well, both the activities and the resulting software have economic attributes (they have costs, require resources and have value).
Software engineering economics then provides a way to study the attributes of software and its processes in order to systematically relate them to economic measures with the aim of making better decisions about them.');

The discipline of Software Engineering is based on Computer Science and as such, its importance is absolutely invaluable and crucial for its body of knowledge. A software engineer needs knowledge about the computer: its hardware, software, types of computers, programming paradigms, computer networks, compilers, databases, etc.');

Mathematics is a discipline concerned with the formal study of systems. Its intervention at the level of software engineering has a direct influence on techniques for identifying a set of rules for reasoning in the context of systems under study. Its strands of language and logic are also important for describing mathematical proofs about certain problems and developing an algorithmic solution for them.');

It is the difference between this statement and another more empirical approach that allows Software Engineering to be recognized as a fully legitimate engineering discipline. As such, this KA addresses the aspects that apply to software engineering and other engineering disciplines, such as measurement, experimental techniques, or statistical analysis.');



                                                  















                                                                






                                                                            
                                                                           

                                                                           
                                                                           
                                                                           


